<font color="#FF0000">LOSING IT ALL!</font><br>
<tt>Sat Jul 26 19:42:36 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
I almost every group that I have attended or participated in there always seems to be a lot of pain related to the loss of children.  I had a wife and three children that I lost because I couldn't think straight (not drugs or alcohol.)  I chased all over the world seeking sensation and an escape.  In the early `80's I decided to hang up my flight helmet and become a &quot;Good Daddy.&quot;<br>
God blessed me with a little girl, born over two months pre-mature.  I named her Rachael.  She made life worth living.  I lost her a couple of years later and I descended to the bottom of the pit.<br><br>
&quot;Rachael is Gone&quot;<br><br>
The little rag doll sits in a chair<br>
and has no one to hold her.<br>
Her empty face reflects despair<br>
and makes the room seem colder.<br>
She yearns for Rachael's tender care,<br>
as her loneliness grows much stronger.<br><br>
In a cardboard cupboard, that she erected,<br>
all the tin dishes are gathering dust.<br>
It seems too long, they've been neglected.<br>
They fear the encroaching rust.<br>
Rachael's small hands are soon expected.<br>
She shall return to them, they trust.<br><br>
A tiny toothbrush hangs by the sink<br>
and knows that something has gone awry.<br>
Her slender handle blushes pink.<br>
Her soft bristles are far too dry.<br>
&quot;Rachael is coming back,&quot; I think,<br>
&quot;If not, then I shall die.&quot;<br><br>
The jar of candies waits on the shelf<br>
and fears the wretched tale,<br>
Without Sweet Rachael to help herself,<br>
they know they will all go stale.<br>
Surely, justice will right itself,<br>
and sticky fingers again prevail.<br><br>
But, no one hurst like Rachael's Dad,<br>
since Rachael has been taken away.<br>
He walks the floor, broken and sad,<br>
while everything screams to say,<br>
&quot;Rachael's daddy would be so glad<br>
if she would come home to play.&quot;<br><br>
Springtimes come and summers go,<br>
and dusks turn into dawn.<br>
Bright petals fall from stalks that grow,<br>
while leaves blanket the empty lawn.<br>
But, I will need no Santa or Christmas snow,<br>
now that Rachael is gone.<br><br>
